WEBVTT

00:01.376 --> 00:02.878
CHARLES:
We need to find someone who knew him.

00:02.878 --> 00:06.715
‐ They're holding a memorial for
Tim Kono in the lobby in 10 minutes.

00:06.715 --> 00:09.259
‐ I'm sure we're all grieving
the loss of Tim Kono.

00:09.259 --> 00:11.220
‐ Ooh, a therapist is
always a fun suspect.

00:11.220 --> 00:14.348
‐ I lived next to that miserable
man for eight years,

00:14.348 --> 00:16.016
and I need those extra rooms.

00:16.016 --> 00:18.894
‐ Wouldn't be the first New Yorker
to kill for good real estate.

00:18.894 --> 00:20.521
Were you close to Tim?

00:20.521 --> 00:22.564
‐ My cat. She died last night.

00:22.564 --> 00:25.901
‐ I really did not want this
to become a regular thing,

00:25.901 --> 00:27.903
but I am strapped.
‐ Dad.

00:29.196 --> 00:31.448
‐ Your building fees are
eight months past due.

00:31.448 --> 00:32.741
Don't fuck with me, Oliver.

00:32.741 --> 00:34.576
‐ I would love to look at those complaints

00:34.576 --> 00:35.869
about Tim Kono.

00:35.869 --> 00:38.038
‐ Buy two, and I'll throw in the file.
Buy three,

00:38.038 --> 00:41.166
and I'll fill you in on the stuff
that was too juicy to write down.

00:41.166 --> 00:43.710
‐ You can't disappear
for 10 years, then show up

00:43.710 --> 00:46.129
and start dragging up a bunch
of shit from when we were kids.

00:46.129 --> 00:48.507
‐ Oscar's getting out, Tim.
You can make things right.

00:48.507 --> 00:49.716
You know what happened that night.

00:49.716 --> 00:52.135
‐ They're cleaning out
Tim Kono's apartment tomorrow,

00:52.135 --> 00:54.847
so we're gonna look around
for clues before everything's gone.

00:54.847 --> 00:57.599
Bloody cat prints!
‐ My beautiful Evelyn.

00:57.599 --> 00:59.726
‐ The cat was here after Tim died.

00:59.726 --> 01:02.771
I think our list of suspects
just got a little longer.

01:02.771 --> 01:04.273
♪

01:06.108 --> 01:09.111
♪ bombastic Broadway‐style music ♪

01:21.331 --> 01:25.460
‐ This is Splash! The Musical.

01:25.460 --> 01:27.546
Not squirt. Not tinkle.

01:28.380 --> 01:30.215
Splash!
TEDDY: Oliver,

01:30.215 --> 01:32.217
you said this was a social dinner.

01:32.217 --> 01:33.969
‐ Well, it's a good thing dinner's over

01:33.969 --> 01:37.389
because I have this
new idea for the set.

01:37.389 --> 01:39.975
‐ We already built a set.
‐ Y‐you're four mill over budget.

01:39.975 --> 01:43.395
‐ No, no, no, no. W‐w‐we need
a set that no one has seen.

01:44.313 --> 01:47.357
A pier high above the stage.

01:47.357 --> 01:50.319
A pool built directly into the floor.

01:50.319 --> 01:52.196
‐ A pool?
‐ Yeah, picture it.

01:52.196 --> 01:55.157
You're dancing,
kickin' up water like Singin' In The Rain.

01:56.074 --> 01:57.784
Then,

01:57.784 --> 01:59.661
you lower the floor...
[sliding]

01:59.661 --> 02:00.746
[gasps]

02:00.746 --> 02:03.749
And you can dive down! Splash!

02:04.249 --> 02:07.586
And do some fantastic synchronized
swimming choreography.

02:07.586 --> 02:09.129
‐ This seems insane.

02:10.088 --> 02:12.132
Right, Teddy?
‐ When isn't it?

02:12.132 --> 02:13.217
OLIVER:
Teddy...

02:13.884 --> 02:15.886
look at Roberta, please.

02:17.054 --> 02:18.096
‐ Hello, Roberta.

02:19.056 --> 02:21.099
‐ Hi, Teddy.
‐ Now...

02:21.099 --> 02:23.852
[Roberta giggles]
...picture me at 28.

02:23.852 --> 02:26.480
The opening night of
my first Off‐Broadway show.

02:26.480 --> 02:28.732
Way off. Off, off, off, off, off.

02:28.732 --> 02:32.444
And I look across the room,
and I see this beautiful woman,

02:32.444 --> 02:35.364
totally out of my league.

02:35.364 --> 02:38.033
And I figure, if I've got a shot,

02:38.033 --> 02:40.035
I gotta go all in.

02:40.035 --> 02:41.745
♪

02:41.745 --> 02:44.373
So I slowly saunter over, and I say,

02:44.373 --> 02:46.583
"Oh, hello. I'm Oliver Putnam,

02:46.583 --> 02:49.586
and I would like to take you
to dinner right now."

02:49.586 --> 02:51.547
And she smiles and says,

02:51.547 --> 02:52.798
"Fat chance."
‐ "Hell no."

02:53.507 --> 02:56.218
‐ And then I said, "How about a snack?"
[Roberta laughs]

02:56.218 --> 02:58.470
‐ Who says no to a snack?

02:58.470 --> 03:01.181
‐ So we go to the Shining Star Diner
across the street,

03:01.181 --> 03:04.434
and I tell her that I will, some day,

03:04.434 --> 03:08.021
direct every big Broadway show,

03:08.021 --> 03:11.066
and, some day, I'm going to marry her.

03:11.650 --> 03:13.944
And she laughs and says,

03:13.944 --> 03:14.945
"Sure you will."
‐ "Hell no!"

03:14.945 --> 03:18.073
‐ And then I point over here
to the Arconia, and I say,

03:18.073 --> 03:21.618
"And, some day,
I'm gonna live in that place."

03:21.618 --> 03:23.120
And Roberta says...

03:24.288 --> 03:25.455
‐ "Now, you're talking."

03:25.455 --> 03:27.749
[both laugh]
OLIVER: Teddy,

03:27.749 --> 03:31.545
look who married way out of his league
and lives four floors above you.

03:31.545 --> 03:33.380
[Teddy sighs, laughs]

03:33.380 --> 03:35.257
All that we have done together.

03:36.008 --> 03:37.259
This is our big one.

03:38.886 --> 03:41.430
You gotta dive all in with me.

03:41.430 --> 03:44.433
♪

03:45.267 --> 03:47.019
‐ [sighs] Oliver...

03:50.522 --> 03:52.191
I do like the pool.

03:52.191 --> 03:54.151
‐ Ha!
[laughter]

03:54.151 --> 03:57.154
Let me top you off.
‐ Fine, but just a splash.

03:57.154 --> 03:58.864
[laughs]

03:58.864 --> 04:01.241
‐ Let's all make a fuckin' splash,

04:01.241 --> 04:03.368
shall we?
[glasses clink]

04:03.368 --> 04:06.371
♪ lively theme song playing ♪

04:06.371 --> 04:09.374
♪ vocalizing ♪

04:50.374 --> 04:53.377
♪ concertina playing ♪

04:57.506 --> 05:00.509
♪

05:09.935 --> 05:11.186
♪ concertina continues ♪

05:11.186 --> 05:13.438
CHARLES:
How well do you know your neighbors?

05:13.438 --> 05:15.649
You see many of them every day,

05:15.649 --> 05:19.027
but have you ever wondered,
could they harm me?

05:19.027 --> 05:21.196
Or even kill?

05:21.196 --> 05:24.908
Tim Kono was murdered
by someone in this building,

05:24.908 --> 05:26.618
which means‐‐
‐ Okay, I'm sorry. Cut.

05:26.618 --> 05:27.494
‐ What's the matter?

05:28.036 --> 05:29.997
‐ You are scoring a murder mystery,

05:29.997 --> 05:32.124
not DJing a hobbit's wedding.

05:32.124 --> 05:35.169
‐ The concertina can be very haunting.
It transports.

05:35.169 --> 05:38.463
‐ Yeah well, it transports me
back to 1800s Ireland.

05:38.463 --> 05:40.465
I feel like I'm in the middle
of the Potato Famine.

05:40.465 --> 05:41.800
[playing]

05:41.800 --> 05:44.928
Don't I get a say after I invested
in all this lovely equipment?

05:44.928 --> 05:46.555
‐ I'm not paying for any
of this, by the way.

05:46.555 --> 05:48.348
‐ Of course not!

05:48.348 --> 05:51.935
I wasn't gonna ask you to chip in,
even though it is... our podcast.

05:51.935 --> 05:54.188
‐ Let's see if Mabel's free.
I'll call her.

05:55.397 --> 05:56.523
Or should I text?

06:00.068 --> 06:02.237
‐ Calls bother them for some reason.

06:02.237 --> 06:04.573
‐ Yeah. I think it's a text.

06:04.573 --> 06:05.824
[knocking]

06:08.160 --> 06:09.995
What sounds more casual?

06:09.995 --> 06:12.039
"Dear Mabel" or "Greetings, Mabel"?

06:14.249 --> 06:15.459
‐ Hey.

06:15.459 --> 06:17.836
[elevator dings]
Ooh, our last Gut Milk shipment.

06:17.836 --> 06:19.922
‐ Your next Gut Milk shipment.

06:19.922 --> 06:21.298
[Oliver growls]
Plus,

06:21.298 --> 06:24.551
I wrote down everything I could
about that shit ball Tim Kono.

06:24.551 --> 06:26.386
May he rest in peace. But,

06:26.386 --> 06:29.431
if anybody catches you with this...
‐ I will burn it

06:29.431 --> 06:31.850
and snort the ashes like it's 1982.

06:31.850 --> 06:35.229
Don't you worry.
‐ [laughs] Oh, and this is from Bunny.

06:37.523 --> 06:40.359
‐ "If you do not pay
within the next 24 hours,

06:40.359 --> 06:43.278
your water and power will be shut off."
She said I had two weeks!

06:43.278 --> 06:44.947
‐ She wants your ass out, baby.

06:44.947 --> 06:46.949
Gotta give Bunny her money!

06:48.784 --> 06:50.494
[sighs]

06:53.997 --> 06:57.209
‐ Hey! I figured out the perfect
greeting for the text!

06:57.209 --> 06:58.210
[text chimes]

07:00.629 --> 07:01.630
[text chimes]

07:05.551 --> 07:08.554
[typing, text chimes]

07:11.932 --> 07:12.933
[text chimes]

07:13.851 --> 07:14.852
[text chimes]

07:15.394 --> 07:16.395
[text chimes]

07:17.271 --> 07:19.982
[crowd cheering]

07:19.982 --> 07:22.025
[laughs]

07:22.025 --> 07:25.028
♪

07:29.700 --> 07:32.494
‐ And these are...
‐ Candid photos I took of our neighbors,

07:32.494 --> 07:35.789
matched with official complaints
we got from Ursula.

07:35.789 --> 07:38.625
‐ Cool, but why are they all selfies?

07:38.625 --> 07:40.419
‐ So I don't draw suspicion.

07:40.419 --> 07:44.006
‐ I'm sorry, I'm sorry.
So‐so you think that Sting,

07:44.006 --> 07:46.800
musical icon Sting, killed Tim Kono?

07:46.800 --> 07:48.927
‐ I'm just a fan.
He lives in the building,

07:48.927 --> 07:51.263
and I always wanted
a picture with him. You know.

07:51.263 --> 07:54.224
I'll move it over here.
I could get him to sign it later.

07:54.224 --> 07:57.144
‐ How do we even start with these?
‐ Well...

07:57.144 --> 07:59.188
how do you sculpt an elephant?

07:59.188 --> 08:00.772
You start with a block of marble,

08:00.772 --> 08:04.526
and you chip away
everything that isn't elephant.

08:04.526 --> 08:05.861
We do the same thing.

08:05.861 --> 08:08.280
We eliminate everyone who isn't a killer,

08:08.280 --> 08:10.490
until we're left with the person who is.

08:10.490 --> 08:13.911
‐ Intriguing, and yet totally backwards.

08:13.911 --> 08:15.495
When you cast a show, you don't say,

08:15.495 --> 08:17.998
"I'm looking for not a Brad Pitt‐type."

08:17.998 --> 08:19.625
You say who you are looking for.

08:19.625 --> 08:22.753
‐ Alright. I am looking for a guy

08:22.753 --> 08:25.088
I saw going up the stairs

08:25.088 --> 08:26.673
in a tie‐dyed hoodie

08:26.673 --> 08:29.301
the night of the fire alarm when Tim died.

08:30.636 --> 08:34.097
And I'm looking for the mysterious...

08:34.097 --> 08:35.641
Tim's fiancée.
[Oliver groans]

08:35.641 --> 08:38.018
‐ What if tie‐dye guy is the fiancée?

08:38.018 --> 08:39.269
‐ Guys, guys, guys.

08:39.269 --> 08:41.688
We need one lead.

08:41.688 --> 08:43.190
One lead.

08:46.235 --> 08:47.277
Stop!

08:47.611 --> 08:49.696
♪ dramatic sting ♪

08:49.696 --> 08:51.114
I know how to do this.

08:52.574 --> 08:55.577
♪ jazzy Broadway‐style music ♪

08:57.329 --> 08:59.122
[echoing stamp]
Congrats!

08:59.122 --> 09:01.834
On making it this far.

09:01.834 --> 09:04.670
You should all feel very proud indeed.

09:04.670 --> 09:07.881
But as you know, there can only be one

09:07.881 --> 09:10.259
Tim Kono's murderer.

09:10.259 --> 09:12.135
I'm looking for motive.

09:12.135 --> 09:14.179
I'm looking for means.

09:14.179 --> 09:16.181
But most of all...

09:16.890 --> 09:19.434
I'm looking for moxie. [snickers]

09:20.602 --> 09:21.854
Ah!

09:21.854 --> 09:23.814
The needy therapist.

09:23.814 --> 09:26.817
‐ I did it. I'm a bad therapist.

09:26.817 --> 09:27.985
[slapping]

09:27.985 --> 09:30.571
‐ Okay, you know what?
I can't with the neediness.

09:30.571 --> 09:32.531
Step to the back line, please. Quickly.

09:32.531 --> 09:33.532
♪ brassy accent ♪

09:33.532 --> 09:36.535
♪

09:37.411 --> 09:38.912
Okay, ye‐‐ Ladies,

09:38.912 --> 09:41.248
I‐I don't have a clue
what's happening here,

09:41.248 --> 09:42.708
but none of it's interesting.

09:44.960 --> 09:46.003
Ah!

09:46.587 --> 09:49.590
The murderous matriarch from next door.

09:51.300 --> 09:52.885
‐ I did it.

09:52.885 --> 09:54.386
And I would do it again

09:54.386 --> 09:56.430
for the square footage

09:56.430 --> 09:58.015
and that view.

09:58.015 --> 09:59.975
‐ The only view you're going to have

09:59.975 --> 10:01.768
is from the back line!

10:02.769 --> 10:03.770
[sucks tongue]

10:03.770 --> 10:06.773
No one wants a murder podcast
about real estate!

10:08.775 --> 10:09.776
[sighs]

10:13.030 --> 10:16.033
People, you‐you can't look
like you want it too much.

10:17.075 --> 10:19.453
Big mistake.
BUNNY [singing]: Pay your bills!

10:19.453 --> 10:21.830
♪ Pay your bills! ♪

10:21.830 --> 10:23.665
♪ Oliver Putnam ♪

10:23.665 --> 10:26.168
♪ Pay your fucking ♪

10:26.168 --> 10:28.587
♪ Bills! ♪

10:29.129 --> 10:30.839
‐ Bunny, why are you singing?

10:30.839 --> 10:32.966
‐ Well, this is a musical, right?

10:32.966 --> 10:35.677
‐ Not with you in it. Back line!

10:35.677 --> 10:38.680
♪

10:39.598 --> 10:41.266
Ah...

10:42.267 --> 10:44.311
Evelyn's cat daddy.

10:44.311 --> 10:47.397
[papers crinkling]
Oh, had a lot of complaints about Tim.

10:47.397 --> 10:49.441
‐ Tim complained a lot about Evelyn.

10:49.441 --> 10:51.693
He said she gave him asthma attacks.

10:51.693 --> 10:53.070
He threatened to shoot her.

10:53.570 --> 10:55.155
‐ Oh, so you knew Tim had a gun.

10:55.155 --> 10:56.823
‐ That's right.

10:56.823 --> 10:58.951
She had nine lives,

10:58.951 --> 11:01.119
but I cut his one short.

11:01.787 --> 11:03.205
‐ Cute.

11:04.373 --> 11:07.000
Stay put.
‐ Curiosity killed the cat,

11:07.000 --> 11:08.168
but I killed Tim Kono‐‐

11:08.168 --> 11:10.045
‐ Okay, you wanna lose the gig?
Keep talking!

11:11.839 --> 11:13.549
Alright, everyone!

11:13.549 --> 11:15.217
With the exception of Howard Morris...

11:15.217 --> 11:18.220
♪

11:19.263 --> 11:20.514
Back line.

11:26.228 --> 11:28.689
We have our lead.

11:28.689 --> 11:30.691
Howard Morris.

11:30.691 --> 11:32.526
Tim threatened to kill his cat,

11:32.526 --> 11:34.695
and he knew that Tim had a gun.

11:34.695 --> 11:37.114
‐ Plus, those paw prints in Tim's blood.

11:37.114 --> 11:39.283
‐ Correct.
‐ So, what's our plan?

11:39.283 --> 11:41.660
‐ Well, it's an audition.
W‐w‐we meet with him,

11:41.660 --> 11:43.579
bring up Tim Kono, see what he does.

11:43.579 --> 11:45.122
‐ I'm sorry. The plan is

11:45.122 --> 11:48.292
to meet with a murderer,
bring up a dangerous topic till he snaps,

11:48.292 --> 11:51.545
reaches under the sofa, pulls out
the murder weapon, and kills us all?

11:51.545 --> 11:53.338
‐ And we record him.

11:53.338 --> 11:54.923
For the podcast. Ha, ha!

11:54.923 --> 11:57.718
‐ No, no, no. I‐I can't...
Is that even legal?

11:57.718 --> 11:59.303
‐ Oh, that's a good point.

11:59.303 --> 12:01.555
We might have to tell him
he's being recorded.

12:01.555 --> 12:04.141
But subtly, of course,
'cause I don't think he'd like that.

12:04.141 --> 12:05.851
‐ Can I keep this when we're done?

12:05.851 --> 12:08.478
‐ No, no. I have to return all this stuff
in 30 days to get our money back.

12:08.478 --> 12:11.398
‐ No! We can't rush this.
Promise me we're not rushing this.

12:12.107 --> 12:13.108
‐ I'll see you later.

12:13.108 --> 12:14.484
♪

12:14.484 --> 12:18.155
‐ Wait, you're not coming? W‐where are you
gonna be while we interview a murderer?

12:18.155 --> 12:21.158
‐ Oh, just producer stuff.
Boring. Good luck.

12:22.201 --> 12:24.244
‐ What the shit was that?
[door opens]

12:28.373 --> 12:29.374
[sighs]

12:30.709 --> 12:32.211
[doorbell rings]

12:34.963 --> 12:36.465
‐ Hey...

12:37.090 --> 12:38.091
‐ Oliver.

12:38.091 --> 12:41.345
‐ Teddy, my god.
You do not age!

12:41.345 --> 12:44.014
[nervous laughs]
I need the name of your witch!

12:44.473 --> 12:46.683
‐ Oh god. What do you need?

12:46.683 --> 12:48.685
[manic laughter]

12:49.603 --> 12:51.104
Come on in.

12:51.104 --> 12:53.482
[elevator dings]
‐ Now, we need to be careful.

12:53.482 --> 12:56.485
♪

12:57.444 --> 12:59.363
Howard could snap if he feels threatened.

12:59.363 --> 13:01.114
‐ Okay, that's why I think

13:01.114 --> 13:02.908
we should just hit him with the charm.
‐ Good.

13:02.908 --> 13:04.618
Excellent, so I'll take the lead on this.

13:04.618 --> 13:06.912
‐ Excuse me?
‐ Well, I'm an actor.

13:06.912 --> 13:08.580
I can turn on the charm.

13:08.580 --> 13:09.915
‐ Is it on now?

13:10.499 --> 13:12.376
‐ [sighs] It's warming up.
[elevator dings]

13:14.378 --> 13:16.421
‐ Hello...
‐ Hello. Lobby?

13:16.421 --> 13:18.465
‐ Yes, please.
[clicking button]

13:18.465 --> 13:20.384
‐ Oh! I see you're a musician.

13:20.384 --> 13:22.135
‐ Oh, good eye.

13:22.135 --> 13:24.805
I'm actually first chair bassoon
in the City Symphony.

13:24.805 --> 13:27.391
‐ Mm. First chair, Mabel.
She's first chair.

13:27.391 --> 13:29.393
‐ I heard. I don't know what that means.

13:30.853 --> 13:32.980
‐ Wait a minute. Is that your bassoon

13:32.980 --> 13:35.023
I hear playing through
the courtyard every night?

13:35.023 --> 13:37.276
‐ Oh, I'm sorry. I should close my window.

13:37.276 --> 13:40.737
‐ No, it's lovely. I think of it
as the sound of the Arconia.

13:40.737 --> 13:42.906
‐ Oh. That's really sweet. [giggles]

13:44.324 --> 13:46.743
Um, the echoes help me hear my pitch,

13:46.743 --> 13:49.538
and if I need to adjust my embouchure.

13:49.538 --> 13:51.039
‐ Mm. Of course.

13:51.039 --> 13:53.292
Mabel, the embouchure is...

13:53.292 --> 13:54.835
is a mouth position.

13:55.586 --> 13:57.588
‐ Rad.
[elevator dings, doors open]

14:00.424 --> 14:02.551
‐ It was nice meeting you. I'm Jan.

14:02.551 --> 14:04.344
‐ I'm Charles.

14:04.887 --> 14:06.722
‐ Get some, Mr. Savage.

14:06.722 --> 14:09.600
‐ I will not.
‐ Not with that attitude.

14:09.600 --> 14:11.351
[apartment door shuts]
‐ Is my nose bleeding?

14:11.351 --> 14:12.769
‐ No. Well, let's go.

14:12.769 --> 14:16.315
I'm gonna get Howard to talk. You just
make sure he knows he's being recorded.

14:16.315 --> 14:19.234
‐ Right, right. Testing! Testing!

14:20.611 --> 14:22.154
OLIVER:
Some good memories, huh, Teddy?

14:22.738 --> 14:24.948
Makes me so happy seeing them up.

14:24.948 --> 14:27.492
‐ It would be nice if I had
posters of the shows

14:27.492 --> 14:28.952
you talked me out of investing in.

14:29.661 --> 14:31.330
Les Mis?
‐ Yeah, I know.

14:31.330 --> 14:33.957
‐ "It's such a downer, Teddy,
and all over a loaf of bread?"

14:33.957 --> 14:35.959
‐ Well, it was.
‐ Mamma Mia.

14:35.959 --> 14:37.878
"I didn't like ABBA when they were ABBA."

14:37.878 --> 14:39.087
‐ Yeah.
‐ Hamilton.

14:39.087 --> 14:42.090
‐ They picked the one
Founding Father with no pizazz.

14:42.883 --> 14:44.760
That was wrong...
TEDDY: Look, Oliver,

14:44.760 --> 14:48.055
I don't mean to rush.
Uh, you know my son, Theo.

14:48.055 --> 14:49.598
We have a thing we need to‐‐

14:49.598 --> 14:50.682
[mouthing]

14:51.350 --> 14:53.602
‐ I‐I won't be long. I promise.

14:53.602 --> 14:55.395
Can you‐‐ Can you sign that to him?

15:00.651 --> 15:01.944
Thank you!

15:02.444 --> 15:04.780
So‐so Teddy, um... [clears throat]

15:04.780 --> 15:06.907
I'm doing a podcast.

15:06.907 --> 15:10.285
A true crime podcast about a murder

15:10.285 --> 15:12.788
that took place in our own building.

15:14.623 --> 15:16.750
Raise your hand if you just got chills.

15:18.126 --> 15:20.754
But‐‐ And it isn't just the story
of a man's death.

15:20.754 --> 15:23.423
It is about our craving for truth.

15:23.423 --> 15:25.843
Our hunger for justice.

15:25.843 --> 15:29.263
And that's why I think Dimas Delis
is the obvious sponsor.

15:29.263 --> 15:32.099
‐ Hold on. You're really
asking me for money?

15:32.099 --> 15:34.017
‐ Well, I wouldn't, uh, put it like that.

15:34.017 --> 15:37.020
I‐I'm just saying that you can advertise

15:37.020 --> 15:40.190
for the very low cost of $32,000.

15:40.190 --> 15:43.068
‐ Oliver! Motherfucking hell!
‐ Oh, come on, Teddy,

15:43.068 --> 15:45.237
I know there's a part
of you that misses me,

15:45.237 --> 15:48.031
and misses the magic we made.
‐ Oliver, I loved our shows.

15:48.031 --> 15:50.701
It's setting money on fire
I don't care for.

15:50.701 --> 15:52.786
But listen, let's grab a drink some time.

15:52.786 --> 15:54.538
‐ Oh, I would love that. When is good?

15:54.538 --> 15:57.207
‐ When it doesn't cost me 32K.
‐ Ah.

15:57.207 --> 16:00.210
♪

16:00.210 --> 16:02.337
[shuts door]
[exhausted sigh]

16:02.337 --> 16:03.755
What a putz.

16:03.755 --> 16:06.133
[patting couch]
MABEL: Uh,

16:06.133 --> 16:08.093
hi, Howard.

16:08.719 --> 16:10.554
We just wanted to see

16:10.554 --> 16:13.015
how you were holding up since Evelyn.

16:13.015 --> 16:14.474
‐ Thank you.

16:14.474 --> 16:15.809
I wish I were dead.

16:19.521 --> 16:21.899
I'm sorry. Things have
gotten a bit away from me.

16:21.899 --> 16:24.067
‐ Oh, it's okay. Um,

16:24.067 --> 16:26.069
do you have another cat, Mr. Morris?

16:26.069 --> 16:28.739
‐ No. This is all Evelyn's.

16:28.739 --> 16:30.741
If I don't touch anything‐‐

16:30.741 --> 16:33.243
food, water, toys...

16:34.244 --> 16:35.913
I can pretend she's still here.

16:36.371 --> 16:39.875
‐ You know, I heard this once,
and maybe you can appreciate it.

16:39.875 --> 16:42.878
A cat never really leaves you

16:42.878 --> 16:45.172
because they transmit parasites.

16:49.885 --> 16:52.429
‐ I'm sure Evelyn was very clean.

16:52.429 --> 16:54.097
‐ She was. Thank you.

16:54.097 --> 16:57.267
‐ It seems like everyone
in the building loved her.

16:57.267 --> 16:58.227
‐ Mm‐hmm.

16:58.227 --> 16:59.978
‐ Unlike Tim Kono.

17:01.396 --> 17:03.732
I'm sorry, I just...

17:03.732 --> 17:05.567
I link them because...

17:05.567 --> 17:07.861
they both died the same day.

17:08.487 --> 17:11.573
‐ Right.
‐ And people didn't really like Tim Kono.

17:11.573 --> 17:13.951
‐ No, people did not.

17:13.951 --> 17:14.952
I hear.

17:15.452 --> 17:18.205
‐ Really? What did
you hear exactly? Just...

17:18.205 --> 17:19.957
‐ I shouldn't speak ill of the dead.

17:19.957 --> 17:21.250
‐ Tim was a prick.

17:21.250 --> 17:22.835
‐ Yes, he certainly fuckin' was.

17:22.835 --> 17:25.128
‐ We saw him on
the elevator the other day.

17:25.128 --> 17:27.089
‐ What did he do? That fuck.

17:27.089 --> 17:29.466
‐ He berated someone over the phone.

17:29.466 --> 17:31.426
‐ [laughs] Yeah. Typical Tim.

17:31.426 --> 17:33.929
‐ Something about a missing ring...

17:33.929 --> 17:35.180
‐ Hm.

17:35.180 --> 17:36.849
He was always upset about something.

17:37.808 --> 17:39.059
It got worse recently.

17:39.601 --> 17:40.811
I heard

17:40.811 --> 17:43.730
that he got fired from his investment firm

17:43.730 --> 17:46.400
for losing a big client a lot of money.

17:46.400 --> 17:48.068
‐ Really?
‐ Mm‐hmm.

17:48.068 --> 17:50.362
‐ Did Tim ever get upset with Evelyn?

17:50.362 --> 17:52.447
‐ What kind of person

17:52.447 --> 17:54.408
leaves their window open,

17:54.408 --> 17:57.327
and then gets mad
at a cat for wandering in?

17:58.036 --> 18:01.748
Evelyn wasn't a vindictive girl,
but I know that she is happy Tim is dead.

18:04.042 --> 18:06.295
‐ Hm. Uh...

18:08.422 --> 18:10.674
My god, she's beautiful.

18:10.674 --> 18:12.634
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ That's not Evelyn.

18:12.634 --> 18:14.636
‐ Oh.

18:14.636 --> 18:17.097
I could've sworn‐‐
HOWARD: That's Barbara.

18:17.097 --> 18:18.682
She was a bitch.

18:18.682 --> 18:22.311
‐ Yeah. Still, it's so nice
that she's up there, too,

18:22.311 --> 18:23.979
because it's like...

18:23.979 --> 18:25.814
[quietly]
you're being recorded.

18:26.440 --> 18:28.650
‐ What was that?
‐ I said...

18:28.650 --> 18:30.444
she's watching you,

18:30.444 --> 18:32.112
so it's like...

18:32.112 --> 18:33.739
you're being recorded.

18:34.656 --> 18:37.576
‐ I‐I wouldn't put it that way.
Why would you say it like that?

18:37.576 --> 18:41.246
‐ Uh, I... I don't know.

18:41.246 --> 18:44.166
You were saying Evelyn
was happy that Tim died?

18:44.166 --> 18:45.125
[clang]

18:45.125 --> 18:47.044
Whoa! Jesus!
‐ What did you do?

18:47.669 --> 18:49.671
‐ Oh, sorry. Sorry.
[crunch]

18:50.464 --> 18:52.007
‐ What is wrong with you?

18:55.511 --> 18:57.054
[thud]

18:57.054 --> 18:58.514
‐ What the fuck! Oh my god!

18:58.514 --> 19:00.682
Go get ice! Ice! Go!

19:00.682 --> 19:01.767
Shit.

19:01.767 --> 19:02.935
♪

19:02.935 --> 19:04.394
‐ Ice.

19:04.394 --> 19:06.647
[gasps]
MABEL: Uh...

19:06.647 --> 19:07.940
Just get ice!

19:07.940 --> 19:09.358
‐ Ice?

19:09.358 --> 19:11.985
[wheezing] Ice. Oh my god.

19:11.985 --> 19:13.737
Uh...
[plastic crinkling]

19:13.737 --> 19:15.656
Ah! [gasps]
[crack]

19:15.656 --> 19:16.990
Jeez...

19:16.990 --> 19:19.117
MABEL:
Will you hurry? What the fuck!

19:19.117 --> 19:20.118
[gasps]

19:20.118 --> 19:21.370
‐ God...

19:23.580 --> 19:25.582
‐ You're taking too long!
[Charles gasps]

19:26.667 --> 19:28.669
Hurry, Brazzos!

19:31.129 --> 19:34.091
Oh my god, oh my god, uh... Quick!

19:34.091 --> 19:35.676
Howard, are you okay?

19:35.676 --> 19:36.677
[Howard groans]

19:39.221 --> 19:41.098
I have vasovagal syncope.

19:41.098 --> 19:43.058
I‐I‐I faint at the sight of blood.

19:43.058 --> 19:44.476
‐ Oh.

19:44.476 --> 19:46.103
Well, that‐‐ that sucks.

19:46.562 --> 19:47.938
Probably keeps you from

19:47.938 --> 19:50.274
doing a lot of things,

19:50.274 --> 19:53.277
like being present for bloody murders.

19:54.945 --> 19:56.446
‐ You know,

19:56.446 --> 19:58.574
there's a cat in your freezer.

19:58.574 --> 20:00.284
HOWARD:
Yes, I know that.

20:00.284 --> 20:03.412
I think Tim poisoned Evelyn,
and then killed himself.

20:04.371 --> 20:06.665
I'm getting a toxicology report done.

20:06.665 --> 20:08.166
‐ Makes sense.

20:08.166 --> 20:10.669
It's just that she's next to your food...

20:12.421 --> 20:13.630
Touching it.

20:15.382 --> 20:18.385
♪ playing somber piece ♪

20:30.480 --> 20:31.982
[hits loud note, stops]

20:33.150 --> 20:34.568
[sighs]

20:46.914 --> 20:48.749
[shuts door]
‐ Is it cancer?

20:48.749 --> 20:51.376
I just need to know how
invested I should get in you.

20:51.376 --> 20:53.962
You don't adopt a 20‐year‐old dog.
‐ I'm not dying.

20:53.962 --> 20:56.465
It's anxiety. It happens sometimes
when I talk to people.

20:56.465 --> 20:58.842
But I have it managed.
I just don't talk to people.

20:58.842 --> 21:01.220
Or go on dates. Or know my neighbors.

21:01.220 --> 21:02.346
‐ Well, you know me.

21:02.346 --> 21:04.890
‐ And you are?
‐ Not going to laugh at that.

21:04.890 --> 21:06.225
‐ I don't blame you.
[pushes button]

21:06.225 --> 21:08.435
I'm gonna get some air.
[Mabel sighs]

21:08.435 --> 21:09.811
‐ So I guess Howard is alibied out.

21:09.811 --> 21:12.856
‐ What? You bought that? The fainting act?

21:12.856 --> 21:15.067
I can spot actors a mile away.

21:15.067 --> 21:16.401
Any word from Oliver?

21:18.237 --> 21:19.905
‐ Nothing.
[Charles sigh]

21:19.905 --> 21:22.616
[elevator dings]
‐ My agent always said he was unreliable.

21:22.616 --> 21:24.618
She said, "Don't even
go audition for him."

21:24.618 --> 21:27.037
'Course it's moot because I'm offer‐only‐‐
‐ Bye!

21:27.037 --> 21:29.456
‐ Uh, bye. [sighs]
[button clicks, doors shutting]

21:30.040 --> 21:31.041
[elevator dings]

21:35.587 --> 21:37.589
What are you up to?

21:37.589 --> 21:38.841
[Oliver growls]

21:40.259 --> 21:41.510
‐ Jesus.

21:42.553 --> 21:45.556
♪

21:48.642 --> 21:50.936
Original posters like this

21:50.936 --> 21:53.272
go for five, sometimes 10,000.

21:54.189 --> 21:56.608
And I'm a little strapped right now.

21:56.608 --> 21:59.653
‐ You can't sell this.
Wasn't this your biggest show?

21:59.653 --> 22:02.072
‐ No, no. This was my biggest flop.

22:02.072 --> 22:04.825
‐ Oh. There were bigger flops.

22:04.825 --> 22:07.119
‐ Oh, no, no. No, no, no.

22:07.119 --> 22:10.205
There is no bigger flop than my show.

22:10.205 --> 22:13.208
We got bad reviews before we even opened.

22:13.500 --> 22:16.879
You didn't see water
on a stage for 10 years.

22:18.839 --> 22:21.592
It caused three bankruptcies,
two insurance investigations.

22:21.592 --> 22:23.635
‐ I'm sure it had some good moments.

22:24.553 --> 22:25.971
‐ Well,

22:25.971 --> 22:28.473
at the end of the first act,
there was this amazing number

22:29.391 --> 22:31.852
where 12 merman dove from a high pier

22:31.852 --> 22:34.396
into a pool built into the stage floor.

22:35.647 --> 22:38.859
But, the first night of previews,

22:38.859 --> 22:41.528
they'd been having problems
with the hydraulics

22:41.528 --> 22:43.906
that lowered the floor.

22:45.157 --> 22:46.658
But, I said...

22:48.994 --> 22:51.288
"Go for it."
‐ Uh‐huh.

22:51.288 --> 22:53.165
♪ Broadway‐style music ♪

22:53.165 --> 22:56.168
‐ And as each merman sang,
"Make a splash..."

22:57.836 --> 23:01.048
they all dove down from the high pier,

23:01.048 --> 23:02.591
one by one.

23:02.591 --> 23:05.802
MERMEN [singing]:
Make a splash! Make a splash...

23:05.802 --> 23:09.056
‐ And I can still hear the sound
of them all hitting the floor.

23:09.890 --> 23:12.726
Thwop.
[thud, crowd screaming]

23:12.726 --> 23:14.478
Thwop.
[thud]

23:15.187 --> 23:17.940
Thwop.
[screaming continues]

23:17.940 --> 23:20.067
Thwop.
[thud]

23:20.067 --> 23:21.193
‐ All 12?

23:22.277 --> 23:23.904
‐ All 12.

23:24.821 --> 23:27.074
Chorus boys tend to stick together.

23:28.116 --> 23:30.953
‐ Well, you made a mistake.
We all make mistak‐‐

23:30.953 --> 23:32.412
No one died, right?
‐ No.

23:32.412 --> 23:34.706
‐ Yeah, well, okay. We all make mistakes.

23:34.706 --> 23:36.667
‐ The headline in the Times next day was,

23:36.667 --> 23:39.211
"Splat."
‐ Well, if that's the worst of it.

23:39.711 --> 23:41.338
‐ No, it's not.

23:42.214 --> 23:44.216
I put my own money in the show.

23:45.259 --> 23:47.594
But, it wasn't actually...

23:47.594 --> 23:49.972
mine. It was my son's college fund.

23:52.182 --> 23:55.310
I not only lost my career with the show,

23:56.061 --> 23:58.438
but making it all about me...

23:59.857 --> 24:01.984
I lost my family as well.

24:02.985 --> 24:05.153
‐ It can happen.

24:05.153 --> 24:06.905
Trust me, I know.

24:06.905 --> 24:09.908
You can lose a lot with one big mistake.

24:12.077 --> 24:13.078
[sighs]

24:15.038 --> 24:18.166
But the world needs Oliver Putnams.

24:18.166 --> 24:20.586
You push people out of their comfort zone.

24:20.586 --> 24:22.546
I mean, I don't like to
get involved with people,

24:22.546 --> 24:24.381
but I just met a very strange man,

24:24.381 --> 24:27.342
and knocked a frozen cat
out of his freezer.

24:28.635 --> 24:30.762
I‐I still have its leg!

24:30.762 --> 24:31.763
‐ Oh, Jesus!

24:32.514 --> 24:34.600
‐ It's warm now,

24:34.600 --> 24:36.935
and that smell is new,

24:36.935 --> 24:38.812
but it's also kinda thrilling,

24:38.812 --> 24:40.647
and it's all because of you.

24:40.647 --> 24:42.357
I mean, you're insane,

24:42.357 --> 24:44.318
but that's usually who
people want to follow.

24:44.735 --> 24:46.028
You can't lose that.

24:46.737 --> 24:48.071
‐ You know, I spent all day

24:48.071 --> 24:50.532
looking for some cash to
make this podcast special.

24:50.532 --> 24:53.619
‐ You know, let me put some money into
that sound equipment. It's our show.

24:53.619 --> 24:55.537
‐ Oh, no, no. You don't have to do that.
‐ No, I want to‐‐

24:55.537 --> 24:57.372
‐ You owe me 4,500. I prefer cash.

24:57.915 --> 25:00.000
‐ [mouthing] Where you going?

25:00.000 --> 25:02.878
♪

25:02.878 --> 25:06.381
‐ Oliver Putnam is not gonna
take no for an answer.

25:17.309 --> 25:18.310
[knocking]

25:21.772 --> 25:23.148
‐ Hi, Mr. Torres.

25:23.148 --> 25:24.942
I don't know if you remember me, but‐‐

25:24.942 --> 25:27.277
‐ I do. Do you need something fixed?

25:27.611 --> 25:29.988
‐ N‐no. The apartment is fine.

25:29.988 --> 25:31.532
Everything's fine.

25:31.949 --> 25:34.701
Um, I was just looking for Oscar.

25:34.701 --> 25:36.245
Wasn't he getting out this week?

25:36.245 --> 25:38.163
‐ [sighs] He's not here.

25:38.497 --> 25:41.708
‐ Okay, well, can you tell him
I'm looking for him, and if‐‐

25:41.708 --> 25:43.669
‐ No. I won't do that.

25:44.253 --> 25:45.379
My son needs a fresh start.

25:46.839 --> 25:49.049
Don't come here again.

25:55.681 --> 25:57.057
‐ Time for that drink, Teddy.

25:57.057 --> 25:59.142
‐ Please, don't make me move.

25:59.142 --> 26:01.645
‐ No, no, no, please, please, please.

26:01.645 --> 26:02.729
I‐I...

26:03.689 --> 26:05.190
Do you remember the day

26:05.190 --> 26:07.568
I sold you on the pool for Splash?

26:08.569 --> 26:10.696
You bought in because I was confident

26:10.696 --> 26:12.656
and charming and young.

26:12.656 --> 26:14.658
‐ You were around 58.

26:14.658 --> 26:17.286
‐ Well, that's not the point.

26:17.286 --> 26:20.706
An hour before you got there,
I was so nervous.

26:20.706 --> 26:23.417
Hyperventilating over
what kind of wine to open.

26:23.876 --> 26:25.878
Yet an hour later,

26:25.878 --> 26:28.422
you saw a confident salesman.

26:28.422 --> 26:29.923
But it was all pretend.

26:30.757 --> 26:33.177
The false arrogance of youth.

26:33.177 --> 26:34.720
‐ Again, you were nearly 60.

26:34.720 --> 26:36.555
‐ Yeah, but I'm older now.

26:37.306 --> 26:39.975
And I have learned, Teddy.

26:40.767 --> 26:44.438
No one who promises big things
knows what's gonna happen.

26:45.355 --> 26:47.357
But, it's the ride that counts.

26:48.275 --> 26:50.986
I think I am onto something great here,

26:52.237 --> 26:54.698
and I swear to you,
I'm not gonna let you down.

26:56.241 --> 26:59.620
Let's make a real splash this time.

26:59.620 --> 27:02.122
‐ But with a podcast, Oliver?

27:02.122 --> 27:03.665
‐ Well, it starts with a podcast,

27:03.665 --> 27:05.876
but you know, with me,
it's always gonna be more.

27:05.876 --> 27:07.377
[sighs]

27:09.630 --> 27:11.173
What was it? 32K?

27:11.173 --> 27:13.133
‐ Now, it's 35.

27:13.133 --> 27:14.635
Always more.

27:14.635 --> 27:17.638
♪

27:17.638 --> 27:20.641
[pearls rattling]

27:33.987 --> 27:34.988
[drops magazine]

27:41.370 --> 27:42.871
♪

27:56.343 --> 27:58.095
Come on, girl.

27:59.012 --> 28:01.014
[Winnie grunts]
Ooh, sorry. Let's go.

28:01.014 --> 28:02.641
[elevator dings, doors open]
Oh!

28:02.641 --> 28:04.935
[indistinct chatter]

28:04.935 --> 28:07.688
There we go.
There you go, Winnie.

28:09.356 --> 28:10.440
[doors close]

28:10.440 --> 28:12.985
Well, hello there, Sting!

28:12.985 --> 28:15.779
[sniffing, licking]

28:16.363 --> 28:18.407
‐ Your dog, please.
‐ Oh.

28:18.407 --> 28:21.451
[Winnie snorts]
Winnie, don't stand so close to Sting.

28:22.661 --> 28:26.081
She's just on edge after that
upsetting death the other night.

28:26.665 --> 28:29.334
Which I'm actually doing a podcast about.

28:29.334 --> 28:31.336
Um... [scoffs]

28:31.336 --> 28:33.547
Kind of a bid deal. [laughs]

28:33.547 --> 28:35.674
People seem to think it's a big deal...

28:36.758 --> 28:39.720
Did you, uh, by chance, know Tim Kono?

28:39.720 --> 28:41.972
‐ Are you suggesting I had
something to do with that?

28:41.972 --> 28:43.640
‐ No, no, no, no, no. I‐I was just‐‐

28:43.640 --> 28:46.059
It was just a‐a question in passing.

28:46.059 --> 28:47.895
‐ Please, your dog.
[snorts]

28:47.895 --> 28:48.937
OLIVER:
Yes, I'm sorry.

28:48.937 --> 28:51.481
‐ Control him!
‐ Yes, I'm sorry.

28:51.481 --> 28:52.941
Winnie is just a big fan.
[Winnie sniffing]

28:52.941 --> 28:54.985
‐ I don't like dogs.

28:54.985 --> 28:56.570
‐ Ah. [clears throat]
[sniffing continues]

28:56.570 --> 28:59.198
Do you have a dog?
‐ I have a dog.

28:59.198 --> 29:01.408
I don't like him either.
[doors open]

29:01.783 --> 29:04.578
‐ Ah, well, this‐this has been a...

29:04.578 --> 29:05.954
[clears throat]

29:06.413 --> 29:08.790
♪ concertina playing ♪

29:12.920 --> 29:15.631
♪ playing continues ♪

29:23.555 --> 29:26.141
[stops playing]
‐ You liked it, right?

29:26.141 --> 29:27.893
‐ Is that what my face is saying?

29:28.644 --> 29:31.688
‐ Oh hey! Listen,
uh, uh, before we wrap up,

29:31.688 --> 29:34.441
I have a little announcement to make.

29:34.441 --> 29:38.195
We are now the proud parents of a new...

29:38.195 --> 29:39.947
podcast.
‐ What does that mean?

29:39.947 --> 29:42.074
‐ We just published our first episode.

29:42.699 --> 29:45.953
Or dropped. We‐we dropped it.
Like it was hot. [laughs]

29:45.953 --> 29:48.413
‐ Excuse me, when did we do that?

29:48.413 --> 29:50.499
‐ An hour ago.
‐ I can't find it.

29:50.499 --> 29:54.086
‐ Oh, try Dimas Chicken Wraps Presents

29:54.086 --> 29:55.170
Only Murders in the Building.

29:55.712 --> 29:58.882
I got us a big fat sponsorship. [snorts]

29:58.882 --> 30:01.969
Teddy had one condition.
Because it's Chicken Wrap month,

30:01.969 --> 30:05.097
he needed us to drop
the first episode right away, so...

30:05.097 --> 30:06.974
‐ You rushed it. Big surprise.

30:06.974 --> 30:08.851
This is an Oliver Putnam Production.

30:09.434 --> 30:10.811
How we doing? Any audience?

30:10.811 --> 30:13.021
‐ Found it. Four listens so far.

30:13.021 --> 30:15.023
‐ In only an hour? [laughs]

30:15.023 --> 30:18.569
At this rate, we're gonna be, like,
at two million by... Thursday.

30:19.069 --> 30:20.946
‐ Any comments?
‐ Oh yeah.

30:20.946 --> 30:23.198
"Charles‐Haden Savage is a..."

30:23.991 --> 30:26.493
I‐it's good. It's a‐a good, nice comment.

